-- ── Google Drive ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Google Drive is Google's cloud file storage and synchronization service that lets individuals and teams store, share and collaborate on files from any device.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (15GB shared storage), paid plans from $1.99/month via Google One$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2012, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$180,000+ employees (Alphabet Inc.)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Mountain View, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Korean$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Hindi$q$, $q$Arabic$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Google Drive Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Google Drive review for 2026 covering storage plans, Google One pricing, key features, pros and cons, and how it compares to Dropbox and OneDrive.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Google Drive is Google's cloud storage and file synchronization service, launched on April 24, 2012, extending capability that had previously existed only inside Google Docs into a standalone file storage product with dedicated desktop and mobile apps. It gives individuals, students and businesses a single place to store, sync, share and collaboratively edit files, including native Google Docs, Sheets and Slides documents as well as any uploaded file type such as PDFs, images, videos and archives, accessible through a web interface at drive.google.com, native apps for Windows and macOS, and mobile apps for iOS and Android. Drive is bundled into every Google Account by default, giving every user a shared pool of free storage across Gmail, Google Photos and Drive itself, and it forms the storage backbone of the Google Docs Editors suite and the broader Google Workspace productivity platform. Google Drive is owned and operated by Google, a subsidiary of Alphabet Inc., headquartered in Mountain View, California. As with other core Google products, there is no independent funding or acquisition history for Drive itself since it was built and launched in-house rather than acquired, though its real-time collaborative editing features trace back to Google's 2006 acquisition of Writely, the web-based word processor that became Google Docs, and its 2007 acquisition of Tonic Systems, which became Google Slides. Google consolidated its consumer storage plans in 2015 under the Google One brand, which replaced the earlier Google Drive storage plans and now governs paid storage upgrades across Drive, Gmail and Photos from a single subscription, and in 2018 Google One further expanded to bundle perks like Google Store discounts and expert support alongside storage. Technically, Drive is built around a cloud-synced file system with granular sharing controls at the file, folder and organizational level. Files can be shared with specific people via email invitation, with anyone who has a link, or restricted entirely to the owner, and permissions can be set to viewer, commenter or editor. Real-time collaborative editing is native to Docs, Sheets, Slides, Forms and Drawings, allowing multiple users to edit the same file simultaneously with visible cursors and inline comments. Drive for desktop, the successor to the older Backup and Sync and Drive File Stream clients, lets users mirror or stream their Drive contents to a local file system on Windows and macOS, including offline access to selected files. For organizations, Shared Drives, formerly called Team Drives, provide team-owned storage that persists even when individual members leave, with centralized admin controls, in contrast to personal My Drive folders that are tied to an individual account. Google's Drive API lets third-party developers build integrations that read, write and manage files programmatically, powering everything from backup tools to e-signature and document-management add-ons in the Google Workspace Marketplace. Security features include encryption of data at rest and in transit, version history for tracking and restoring prior file states, and, for Workspace administrators, data loss prevention rules, audit logging and granular sharing restrictions across an organization's domain. Pricing for Drive follows two tracks depending on whether a user is on a personal Google Account or a business Google Workspace account. For personal use, every Google Account includes 15GB of storage shared across Gmail, Drive and Photos at no cost. Beyond that, paid storage is sold through Google One: the Basic plan offers 100GB of storage for $1.99 per month, and the Standard, now bundled under Google's AI-branded subscription naming as part of its 2026 restructuring of consumer plans, offers 2TB of storage for $9.99 per month, with Google increasingly bundling Gemini AI features, such as Gemini in Docs and higher AI usage limits, into these storage tiers rather than selling storage alone. Annual billing typically saves roughly 16 to 17 percent compared to paying month to month. For business users, Drive storage is not purchased separately but is bundled into Google Workspace plans, where Business Starter includes 30GB of pooled storage per user, Business Standard includes 2TB pooled per user, and Business Plus includes 5TB pooled per user, with Enterprise plans offering custom or effectively unlimited pooled storage depending on the agreement. Drive's target audience spans nearly every category of internet user: individual consumers who want free, reliable backup for photos and documents; students and educators who rely on Drive as the default storage layer for Google Classroom assignments; freelancers and small businesses that need lightweight file sharing without standing up their own infrastructure; and large enterprises that adopt Drive as part of a full Google Workspace deployment for company-wide document management, with admin console controls, single sign-on and compliance tooling layered on top. Competitively, Google Drive's closest rivals are Dropbox, Microsoft OneDrive and Box, each of which offers similar cloud storage, sync and sharing capability. Drive differentiates itself primarily through its deep, native integration with Google Docs, Sheets and Slides for real-time collaborative editing, which OneDrive matches for Microsoft Office files but Dropbox and Box do not natively replicate with their own editors, and through the generous 15GB free tier bundled with every Google Account, which is larger than the free tiers most competitors offer. Google's broader ecosystem advantage, single sign-on across Gmail, Search, Android and Workspace, also makes Drive the default choice for anyone already invested in Google's consumer or business products. Its main drawbacks relative to competitors include occasional confusion around Google's shifting storage and AI subscription branding, storage being pooled across Gmail and Photos rather than dedicated solely to files, and enterprise-grade governance features that are generally considered less mature than Microsoft's OneDrive and SharePoint stack for large regulated organizations already standardized on Microsoft 365.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'bd2fce1d-50cd-44a2-927e-39cfe30406dd';

