-- ── Google Gemini ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Google Gemini is Google's family of multimodal AI models and the consumer chat assistant that replaced Bard, offering text, image, code and reasoning capabilities across free and paid tiers.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium / Subscription$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free, paid plans from $9.99/month (Google AI Plus)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2023, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$180,000+ employees (Alphabet Inc.)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Mountain View, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Korean$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Hindi$q$, $q$Arabic$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Google Gemini Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Google Gemini review for 2026 covering the AI model family, chat assistant features, Google AI Plus, Pro and Ultra pricing, pros, cons and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Google Gemini is Google's family of multimodal large language models and the consumer-facing AI chat assistant built on top of them, occupying the same category as OpenAI's ChatGPT and Anthropic's Claude. Gemini was first announced on December 6, 2023, as a natively multimodal model family capable of reasoning across text, images, audio, video and code, and Google initially deployed a tuned version of Gemini Pro inside its existing Bard chatbot before fully rebranding Bard as Gemini on February 8, 2024. That rebrand also folded in Google's separate 'Duet AI' branding, which had been used for AI features inside Google Cloud and Google Workspace, unifying the model, the consumer app, and the enterprise AI features under a single Gemini name so that the underlying model, the chat app and the developer API all share one brand. Gemini is developed by Google DeepMind, the AI research organization formed in April 2023 through the merger of Google Brain and the London-based DeepMind Technologies, which Google had acquired back in 2014. Google DeepMind operates as part of Google, itself a subsidiary of Alphabet Inc., headquartered in Mountain View, California, with major DeepMind research operations continuing out of London. Because Gemini is a product line within Alphabet rather than an independently funded startup, it does not have its own separate venture funding or acquisition history; instead its resources come from Alphabet's overall research and infrastructure budget, one of the largest in the AI industry, and its competitive position is shaped directly by Alphabet's roughly 180,000-plus global workforce and its ownership of foundational compute infrastructure through Google Cloud's custom Tensor Processing Units (TPUs). Technically, the Gemini model family spans multiple size and capability tiers designed for different latency, cost and reasoning needs, historically including Ultra for maximum capability, Pro for balanced general-purpose use, and Flash and Flash-Lite variants optimized for speed and lower cost at high volume, with the lineup continuing to iterate through successive numbered generations. The consumer Gemini app, available on the web, as a dedicated Android and iOS app, and integrated into the Google app and Google Assistant surfaces, supports natural-language conversation, image generation and editing, document and PDF analysis, code generation and debugging, and 'Deep Research' style multi-step web research tasks that compile findings into a structured report. Gemini is also woven directly into Google's own products: Gemini in Gmail can draft and summarize emails, Gemini in Docs can draft and rewrite text, Gemini in Sheets can generate formulas and analyze data, and Gemini in Slides can generate images and speaker notes, all powered by the same underlying model family as the standalone chat app. A long-context window, reaching up to one million tokens on the higher-tier plans, lets Gemini ingest very large documents, codebases or video transcripts in a single prompt, which Google has positioned as a key differentiator against competing chat assistants with smaller context windows. Pricing for the consumer Gemini app follows a freemium subscription model that Google restructured in 2026 under the broader 'Google AI' subscription branding. The free tier gives any user with a Google Account access to a capable Gemini model with standard usage limits, no payment required. Google AI Plus, priced at $9.99 per month, sits at the entry paid tier and expands usage limits and feature access beyond the free plan. Google AI Pro, priced at $19.99 per month and effectively the successor to the earlier 'Gemini Advanced' subscription, unlocks Google's most capable general-purpose Gemini model with a full extended context window, higher compute-based usage limits, a monthly allotment of AI credits usable across image and video generation tools, and 2TB of Google One storage bundled in. At the top, Google AI Ultra was introduced with a list price of $249.99 per month aimed at power users, researchers and developers who need the highest usage ceilings, priority access to Google's most advanced experimental models, and expanded access to tools like Deep Research and video generation; following Google's I/O 2026 announcements, the Ultra tier's price was reduced to $99.99 per month, bringing it closer in line with competing frontier-AI subscription pricing. Google also offers Gemini through a pay-as-you-go developer API, billed per input and output token and varying by model size, which is separate from the consumer app subscriptions and aimed at developers building Gemini into their own products. Gemini's target audience is broad, spanning individual consumers who use the free or Plus tier for everyday writing, research and image generation; students and professionals who upgrade to Google AI Pro for the larger context window, higher usage limits and bundled cloud storage; and developers, enterprises and researchers who either use Google AI Ultra for maximum personal usage ceilings or integrate the Gemini API directly into their own applications, often through Google Cloud's Vertex AI platform for enterprise-grade deployment, data governance and fine-tuning. Competitively, Gemini's most direct rivals are OpenAI's ChatGPT and GPT model family and Anthropic's Claude, with Microsoft Copilot also competing heavily in the productivity-integration space given its deep ties into Microsoft 365. Gemini differentiates itself primarily through its native multimodality across text, image, audio and video from the ground up rather than as a bolted-on capability, its very large context window on higher tiers, and its deep first-party integration across the entire Google product surface, including Search, Gmail, Docs, Android and Google Cloud, an integration breadth that neither OpenAI nor Anthropic can match since they do not own a comparable consumer software ecosystem. Google's ownership of custom TPU infrastructure also gives it a cost and supply-chain advantage in training and serving models at scale compared to competitors that depend more heavily on third-party GPU supply. The main criticisms of Gemini relative to competitors have historically centered on inconsistent output quality and factual reliability in earlier Bard-era releases, confusing and frequently changing subscription tier names and pricing, and a chat interface that some reviewers consider less refined for pure conversational use than ChatGPT, though Google has continued to close this gap with each successive Gemini model generation.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '1769cc92-bed0-46a8-9354-2d81fdae9ad4';

