-- ── goploader ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$goploader is a free, open source, self-hosted file-sharing tool with a Go client and server that lets you upload and encrypt files straight from the terminal using curl, httpie or wget.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$goploader Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$goploader review for 2026 covering this open source Go file-sharing tool, its server-side encryption, terminal workflow, self-hosting setup and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$goploader is a small, open source file-sharing application created by the GitHub user and developer known as Depado, built specifically to make sharing files from a terminal as easy and painless as possible. The project is composed of two parts written entirely in the Go programming language: a lightweight client binary, invoked as 'gpldr,' that uploads a file from the command line, and a server component that receives, stores and serves the uploaded files back out through short, shareable links. According to the project's own documentation, goploader was built as a personal exercise to improve the creator's Go programming skills while producing something genuinely useful, and it was explicitly inspired by 0bin, an existing self-hosted pastebin-style sharing tool, with one key difference: rather than encrypting content client-side in the browser as 0bin does, goploader performs its encryption server-side, simplifying the client considerably and making it fully compatible with plain command-line HTTP clients rather than requiring a JavaScript-capable browser. goploader is not a company or a funded startup; it is an individually maintained open source software project with no corporate ownership, no headquarters and no employee count in the traditional sense, since it is maintained by its creator and a small number of outside contributors in their own time. The project's first tagged stable release, v1.0, shipped on February 9, 2021, and was explicitly described by its author as stable for both the client and the server components. Development has continued at a modest but real pace since then: v1.0.1 was released in February 2024 with dependency updates and bug fixes, and v1.0.2 followed in March 2026 with additional build targets and stripped, statically linked binaries for easier distribution across platforms. As of 2026, the project's GitHub repository has accumulated roughly 300 stars, a modest but respectable following for a single-purpose, developer-oriented utility rather than a mass-market consumer product, and it is released under the permissive MIT License, meaning anyone can use, modify, and redistribute the code, including for commercial purposes, with no royalty or licensing fee. Technically, goploader's server component exposes a simple HTTP API that accepts file uploads and returns a unique, shareable URL for each stored file, while encrypting the stored content server-side so that the raw files are not stored in plaintext on disk. The gpldr command-line client wraps this API in a convenient binary that developers can pipe files into directly from a terminal session, and because the server's HTTP endpoints are designed to be simple and standards-compliant, the same upload workflow also works directly through generic command-line HTTP tools such as curl, httpie and wget without needing the dedicated client at all, which the project's documentation calls out as an explicit design goal. For users who prefer a graphical interface, goploader also ships a basic web interface for browsing and interacting with uploaded files through a standard browser rather than the command line. The project supports multiple installation paths: building from source using the Go toolchain with commands such as 'go build -trimpath -ldflags for the client and server binaries respectively, running the server via a published Docker image with a single 'docker run' command that mounts a persistent data volume and exposes the service on port 8080, or simply downloading pre-built binaries from the project's GitHub Releases page for a given target platform without needing a local Go installation at all. Full project documentation, including setup instructions and configuration reference, is published separately at depado.github.io/goploader. Because goploader is fully open source and self-hosted, its pricing model is simply free: there is no subscription, no usage-based billing, and no vendor-hosted managed version to pay for. The only real cost to running goploader is whatever infrastructure a user or organization chooses to run the server on, whether that is a home server, a small cloud virtual machine, or a container on an existing internal platform, plus the operational time required to deploy, secure and maintain that instance. This stands in contrast to commercial hosted file-sharing and paste services, which typically monetize through storage limits, retention windows, or premium feature tiers behind a subscription. Because there is no company selling goploader as a managed product, there are also no sales-driven feature gates: the entire feature set available in the source code is available to every self-hosting user at no cost, and the project's maintenance model relies on volunteer contributions and the original author's continued interest rather than commercial revenue. goploader's target audience is narrow and technical: individual developers, sysadmins and small teams who want a lightweight, self-hosted alternative to commercial file-sharing or paste services for quickly sending files between machines, colleagues or CI pipelines without relying on a third-party cloud provider. Because it is terminal-first and scriptable, it is particularly well suited to command-line-centric workflows, such as quickly uploading a build artifact, log file or screenshot from a remote server during debugging, piping output from another command straight into an upload, or integrating file sharing into a shell script or CI/CD pipeline where a graphical interface would be inconvenient. Its self-hosted nature also appeals to privacy-conscious users and organizations that want full control over where their shared files are stored and how long they persist, rather than trusting a third-party paste or file-sharing service. In the broader landscape of file and text-sharing utilities, goploader's closest conceptual relatives are 0bin, the project that directly inspired it, along with other lightweight self-hosted sharing tools such as ShareX-compatible custom uploaders, Firefox Send-style ephemeral file-transfer tools (now discontinued as an official Mozilla product), and general-purpose object storage services like Google Cloud Storage or Amazon S3 when used for ad hoc file sharing via signed URLs. goploader differentiates itself from most of these alternatives through its explicit terminal-first philosophy: rather than requiring a browser or a heavier client application, it is built from the ground up to be piped into from a shell, to work seamlessly with generic tools like curl and wget, and to keep the codebase small enough that a single developer can fully understand, audit and modify it, which is a meaningfully different value proposition from large-scale managed cloud storage platforms that prioritize durability, global availability and enterprise compliance over simplicity and self-hostability. Because it is a small, community-maintained project rather than a commercially backed product, users should also weigh the tradeoffs of relying on volunteer-maintained software, including slower response times to security issues, no formal support SLA, and the project's own documentation noting that parts of its technology stack are comparatively dated, which is a common characteristic of small, stable, infrequently updated open source utilities that nonetheless continue to work reliably for their intended narrow purpose.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'ffae92bf-f4f5-40c4-b5cb-88cc30edd135';

