-- ── GoTab ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$GoTab is a restaurant commerce platform combining point of sale, mobile QR ordering, self-service kiosks and tab management for restaurants, bars, breweries and hospitality venues.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (custom quote)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Custom pricing (Basic and Pro tiers, contact sales)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$51-100 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Arlington, Virginia, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$GoTab Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$GoTab review for 2026 covering its restaurant commerce platform, POS, mobile ordering, kiosks and Easy Tab features, pricing tiers, pros, cons and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$GoTab is a restaurant commerce platform that combines point of sale, mobile QR-code ordering and payment, self-service kiosks, and open-tab management into a single integrated system for restaurants, bars, breweries, hotels, food halls and high-volume venues such as stadiums and arenas. Rather than positioning itself purely as a traditional POS replacement, GoTab describes its offering as an entertainment and hospitality commerce platform, built around the idea that guests should be able to open a tab, order, reorder and pay from their own device at any point during their visit, whether they are seated at a table, standing at a bar, or moving between different areas of a venue. The company was founded in 2016 by Tim McLaughlin and is headquartered in Arlington, Virginia, positioning it within the Washington, D.C. metro area's hospitality technology scene rather than Silicon Valley. GoTab has raised a total of roughly 24.1 million dollars in venture funding across several rounds. Its funding history includes an initial 6 million dollar seed round in 2020, an additional 3.5 million dollar round in July 2021 that brought early funding to roughly 9.5 million dollars, and an 18 million dollar Series A round announced in 2023 led by Truist Ventures, which the company described as the largest funding round in its history at the time and used to scale its growing product suite. As of 2026, employee-count estimates for GoTab vary by data provider, with figures ranging from roughly 40 employees at its Arlington headquarters up to the low 80s across all locations, suggesting a lean, focused team relative to the scale of its restaurant and venue customer base. GoTab has been recognized on Inc.'s Regionals Mid-Atlantic list, reflecting its standing as a fast-growing company within its home region. Technically, GoTab's platform is built around several interoperable products that share the same backend order and payment system. The core POS runs on tablets and handheld devices for servers and bartenders, integrating order-taking, kitchen routing and payment processing in one interface. Mobile QR ordering and payment lets guests scan a code at their table or seat to browse a menu, place orders that route directly to the kitchen or bar, and pay without waiting for a server, while GoTab's 'Easy Tab' feature bridges traditional table service with mobile self-service: a server or bartender opens a tab by dipping or tapping a guest's card and capturing their mobile number, GoTab then texts the guest a link to their open tab, and from that point the guest can order, reorder and pay from their phone from anywhere within the venue until they choose to close out. Self-ordering kiosks extend the same ordering and payment engine to a stationary touchscreen format, letting guests browse a menu and pay via credit and debit cards or contactless mobile wallets such as Apple Pay and Google Wallet, with orders routed to the kitchen and guests alerted by text when their order is ready for pickup, a workflow particularly suited to quick-service, food hall and stadium environments where reducing queue time is a priority. Across all of these entry points, GoTab consolidates every order a guest places, regardless of which staff member, kiosk or device took it, onto a single tab that can be settled with one payment, and tabs can travel with a guest as they move from the bar to a table or from an indoor area to a patio. The platform also includes a Marketplace layer for connecting multiple vendors or concepts operating within one venue, tools for managing multiple revenue centers under one account, and reporting and analytics covering sales, labor and guest behavior across locations. GoTab's pricing is not publicly listed as fixed per-location rates; instead the company offers two named tiers, Basic and Pro, with Basic positioned as the more economical option for small-scale and independent restaurants, bars and breweries, and Pro positioned as a more comprehensive suite for larger or multi-location hospitality operations. Both tiers require prospective customers to contact a GoTab account executive for a customized quote and setup estimate, with setup fees similarly tailored to a given venue's specific hardware, integration and configuration needs rather than published as a flat rate. This customized pricing approach is common in the restaurant POS and hospitality technology category, where hardware requirements, payment processing volume, number of terminals, and integration complexity vary significantly from a single independent bar to a multi-location restaurant group or stadium concessions operation, making a one-size-fits-all published price list impractical for most vendors in this space. GoTab's target audience spans independent restaurants, bars and breweries seeking to modernize table service and reduce staffing pressure through guest self-service, hotels and resorts that want integrated food and beverage ordering across multiple outlets, food halls and multi-vendor venues that need a single system spanning several concepts, and high-volume entertainment venues such as stadiums and arenas that need fast, queue-reducing ordering during peak demand. Because the platform is built around flexible order entry points, from a server-operated POS to a fully self-service kiosk, it appeals to operators who want to blend traditional table service with self-service options rather than committing entirely to one model. Competitively, GoTab operates in the restaurant point of sale and commerce platform category alongside Toast, Square for Restaurants, Olo, SpotOn and Aloha, several of which have significantly larger market share and longer operating histories. GoTab differentiates itself primarily through its Easy Tab model, which is more explicitly designed around continuous, portable, guest-controlled tabs that follow a customer through multiple stops within a venue, rather than treating mobile ordering as a bolt-on feature to a traditional table-based POS. This design makes GoTab particularly well suited to bars, breweries, food halls and multi-zone venues where guests naturally move between areas during a single visit, a use case that more traditional, table-anchored POS systems like Toast are not specifically optimized around. GoTab's smaller scale relative to Toast or Square, reflected in its lean employee count and more modest total funding of roughly 24 million dollars compared to the hundreds of millions or billions raised by larger competitors, means it has a smaller partner and integration ecosystem and less brand recognition outside the hospitality industry, but its funding, including the Truist Ventures-led Series A, and its recognition on Inc.'s regional growth lists suggest continued momentum in its specific niche of tab-centric, multi-touchpoint hospitality commerce.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'a57ea53a-5e59-4850-be73-20f61d1184e1';

UPDATE tools SET logo = 'https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?domain=' || regexp_replace(regexp_replace(website, '^https?://', ''), '/.*$', '') || '&sz=256' WHERE id = 'a57ea53a-5e59-4850-be73-20f61d1184e1' AND logo IS NULL AND website IS NOT NULL;

